            <h2>Agriculture and Aquaculture </h2>
            <p>Agricultural runoff occurs when excess fertilizers, pesticides, and other chemicals are washed off of fields during rain events and enter nearby bodies of water. This can lead to eutrophication, harmful algal blooms, and other ecological problems. On the other hand, aquaculture runoff is generated by fish farms and other aquatic operations. Fish waste and uneaten food can accumulate on the bottom of ponds or tanks, and when this material is disturbed it can release nutrients and other pollutants into the surrounding water. Additionally, the use of antibiotics and other chemicals in aquaculture can lead to the development of antibiotic-resistant bacteria and other environmental health risks. Both agricultural and aquaculture runoff can be mitigated through the use of best management practices such as erosion control, nutrient management, and proper waste disposal. Additionally, regulatory frameworks and public awareness campaigns can help to promote sustainable practices and reduce the impacts of non-point source pollution on water resources.</p>
            <a href="https://www.nomomente.org/post/agricultural-runoff-and-water-pollution" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary mt-3">
